{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626369"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:36:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:36:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17071"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17071"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.33,0.25,0.08,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9761"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73522"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9761","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9761"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17071"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58991"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5267"},{"type":"tags","id":"5268"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23105"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73522"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAzole antifungal medications are commonly prescribed for treating fungal infections. They target a specific component of fungal cell metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of azole antifungal drugs?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits lanosterol 14-alpha-demethylase enzyme","Blocks fungal cell wall synthesis","Binds directly to ergosterol in cell membranes","Inhibits protein synthesis at fungal ribosomes","Disrupts microtubule assembly"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAzole antifungals\u003Cstrong\u003E inhibit\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Elanosterol 14-alpha-demethylase\u003C/strong\u003E, an enzyme in the ergosterol biosynthesis pathway. This leads to decreased ergosterol production and accumulation of toxic sterol intermediates, disrupting fungal cell membrane integrity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncorrect mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking fungal cell wall synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with echinocandins, which inhibit beta-glucan synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinding directly to ergosterol\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of polyene antifungals like amphotericin B, not azoles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting protein synthesis at fungal ribosomes\u003C/strong\u003E is not a mechanism associated with azole antifungals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisrupting microtubule assembly\u003C/strong\u003E is not a mechanism utilised by any current antifungal medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe selective toxicity of azoles comes from their higher affinity for fungal cytochrome P450 enzymes compared to human versions, though some cross-reactivity explains their side effects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Azole antifungal drugs work by inhibiting the enzyme lanosterol 14-alpha-demethylase, which disrupts ergosterol synthesis in fungal cell membranes.","Ergosterol is essential for maintaining fungal cell membrane integrity and function.","Azoles are fungistatic rather than fungicidal, meaning they prevent fungal growth rather than directly killing fungi."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58991"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17071"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58991"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T23:10:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T23:12:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9761"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73522"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}